<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFLY: OTHER NEWS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Japanese Leaders Meeting on Economic Package: Leaders of Japan's ruling 
coalition parties were due to meet again today to try to hammer out an 
agreement on how to finance a proposed $49-billion income tax cut. The fragile 
seven-party coalition government headed by Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa had 
intended to announce Thursday an economic stimulus package incorporating the 
tax cut. But it was unable to do so because of fierce opposition from the 
Socialist Party to a Hosokawa plan to balance the cuts with a sales tax 
increase three years from now. 
</P>
</TEXT>
