<HEADLINE>
<P>
HARASSMENT OF WOMEN FOUND RAMPANT AT MILITARY ACADEMIES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Sexual harassment of women is rampant at the nation's military academies and 
up to 97% of female students felt some harassment in 1991, congressional 
investigators said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
 Widespread harassment of women and a prevailing attitude among male recruits 
that women do not belong were detailed in a General Accounting Office report 
presented to the Senate Armed Services personnel subcommittee. 
</P>
<P>
 "Although relatively few cases of sexual harassment were formally reported, 
responses to our survey indicated that nearly all academy women reported 
experiencing at least one form of sexual harassment during the academic year 
1991," GAO military analyst Mark Gebicke told the panel. The GAO is the 
investigating arm of Congress. 
</P>
<P>
 Sen. Dan Coats (R-Ind.) criticized the GAO for drawing so inclusive a 
definition of harassment that the statistics were skewed and that a manageable 
problem appeared to be out of control. Coats said that under the GAO 
definition, a cadet saying, "You'd better shape up," during exercises could be 
accused of harassment by a cadet of the opposite sex. 
</P>
<P>
 The study covered the United States Military Academy at West Point, N.Y., the 
Naval Academy at Annapolis, Md., and the Air Force Academy at Colorado Springs, 
Colo. 
</P>
<P>
 A survey of the class of 1993 at all three academies found that 80% of the 
female cadets either observed or experienced sexist comments in the past year. 
A 1992 Air Force Academy survey found that 78% of all female students and 52% 
of the men said they daily heard sexist or demeaning remarks about women. Women 
make up between 11% and 14% of the student body at the academies. 
</P>
<P>
 Female cadets wrote of being ostracized for reporting blatant incidents of 
harassment. 
</P>
<P>
 Examples of harassment uncovered by the GAO included: 
</P>
<P>
 * Prank phone calls, offhand comments and derogatory name-calling. 
</P>
<P>
 * An upperclassman entering a female student's room and fondling her. 
</P>
<P>
 * A male student videotaping a female student taking a shower. 
</P>
<P>
 * A senior man ordering a woman in a group of underclass trainees to stay 
behind after dismissing others and then attempting to kiss her. 
</P>
</TEXT>
